Wick Geometry Channel – Integrated Design Brief
This brief merges:

What the old code actually does (regression‑first engine with bounded history, sessions, and fallback).

What the current master (“History Fixed”) establishes as the operational scaffold.

What the outside‑in patches demand for the new behavior.

Use it as the single narrative you hand to any future AI/dev.

1. High‑level intent
Wick Geometry Channel is a session‑anchored channel engine that discovers structure “from the outside in.”

A fixed anchor P1 (manual or session) defines the left edge.

From P1 to “now,” the script searches for a dominant parallel family of wicks that acts as the channel rails.

Same‑side pivot pairs define slope; opposite‑side pivots validate.

Outer rails nominate the channel; inner density and midline only refine and score it.

Regression is allowed only as a secondary organizing tool if it survives this geometry, not as the primary source of slope.

2. Operational scaffold (what must be preserved)
The old file and Wick Channels History Fixed share a concrete scaffold that is correct and should not be thrown away.

History bounds

Scan window is from P1 (manual anchor or session start) to an end bar xEnd.

Safety caps (e.g., ~5000 bars) prevent pathological deep scans.

Scan timing

Heavy work runs only when intended (e.g., at barstate.islast for the chart), then redraws lines and labels once.

Pivot detection

Uses a configurable pivot length (pivotLen) and f_is_pivot_high_off / f_is_pivot_low_off with safeHist bounds to avoid out‑of‑range history.

Candidate evaluation

For each candidate end xCur from P1 to scanEnd, the script:

Builds a trend definition (currently regression slope and intercept).

Builds per‑bar midline values, then computes offsets of pivots to that midline.

Bins those offsets into high and low histograms.

Counts touches, inside bars, expansion hits, and length.

Computes a score to pick a best candidate.

Fallback and state

Maintains lastValidBest state so if no better candidate is found, a previously good channel persists.

Uses debug labels to show status: best score, hits, inside %, length, etc.

Drawing lifecycle

Clears all drawnLines on confirmed bars, then calls f_draw_channel once with chosen parameters.

Draws midline, top/bottom rails, parallels, and optional expanded zone using line.new and linefill.new.

This scaffold is your “engine room.” Outside‑in is how it chooses slope and rails; the scaffold is how it runs.

3. Structural change: from regression‑first to outside‑in
Old behavior (code):

Slope/intercept are derived from incremental linear regression over close prices between P1 and xCur using sumX/sumY/sumXY/sumXX.

High and low pivot offsets to that regression midline are binned.

The most common offset bin determines rail distance and sometimes recenters the midline.

New behavior (strategy + patches):

Slope source

Build arrays of same‑side pivots (highs and lows) between P1 and xCur.

For each same‑side pair, compute slope.

Bin slopes within wickRoundTicks * syminfo.mintick tolerance.

Winning slope = bin with most votes.

Intercept = project from the first pivot in the winning pair back to P1.

Rails and width

For a chosen midline (slope, intercept), compute pivot offsets again and bin them.

For each side:

Find the outermost bin (max offset) with at least 2 votes.

Identify the densest bin (max count) as an inner rail.

Channel width comes from outermost qualified offsets, not the densest inner cluster.

Inner rails are secondary structure used for scoring and organization.

Orphan structure

Any non‑winning offset family with at least 3 confirmations becomes an orphan rail.

Orphan offsets and counts are stored in var arrays that persist across bars.

Orphans draw as thin, dotted orange lines around the channel midline.

Scoring

Raw structural score:

expandHits × 30 + railHits × 20 + midTouches × 10 + len × 0.05

Inside factor:

insideFactor = fullInsidePct / 100.0

Final score:

score = structuralScore × insideFactor

minInsidePct remains a hard filter; anything below is discarded before scoring.

No ATR filter; spikes are penalized implicitly by poor containment.

This is the heart of “outside‑in”: rails define slope and width; inner structure and midline follow; regression is demoted to optional helper if used at all.

4. Failure modes and guardrails (from the debugging)
The later patch passes and bug reports add implicit design constraints you should keep in this narrative.

Orphan persistence

Bug: clearing orphan arrays on each redraw meant they never truly persisted.

Rule: orphan rails must live across bars until explicitly invalidated by your lifecycle.

Winner selection

Bug: using strict > for winner votes and not initializing winners when a new bin was created could leave slope or width perpetually na.

Rule: the first valid family must be allowed to win immediately (>= or explicit initialization).

One‑sided channels

Bug: with outermost‑rail logic, sometimes only upper or lower side had enough evidence; code then rejected the candidate.

Rule: when only one side is present, mirror its width to the other side as a fallback so the channel can still form.

“Only orphans draw” mode

Bug: main channel never selected, or slope/intercept stayed na, while orphan logic still accumulated and drew.

Rule: ensure slope, intercept, and width all resolve together for the main winner before validation; if they don’t, skip candidate early, don’t half‑instantiate.

These are not just fixes; they’re part of the strategy: the engine should prefer a good approximate channel that shows structure over showing nothing but orphans.

